// react-dev-lin-lift-edge-cases.scrml
// React developer perspective: edge cases for lin+lift.
//
// Three cases, React lens first:
//   A. lin in if/else branches with lift — the "conditional render" problem
//   B. lin in a loop with lift — the "renderItem()" instinct wall
//   C. lin lifted across a component boundary — the "context without Context"

<program db="./app.db" tables="sessions,content">

${
    function isAdmin() -> boolean { return true }
    function fetchAdminToken() -> string { return "admin-tok-xyz" }
    function fetchUserToken() -> string { return "user-tok-abc" }
}

// ======================================================================
// CASE A: lin in if/else branches with lift
// ======================================================================
// React equivalent:
//   const token = isAdmin ? getAdminToken() : getUserToken()
//   return <p>Authenticated: {token}</p>
//
// That's trivial in React. The question in scrml: does lin play nicely with
// if-as-expression? Answer from the spec (§34.4.2, §17.6): yes, with the
// if-as-expression form. Both branches lift a value, the result binds to lin.
// The consumption is the binding itself. Then token is lifted once to markup.
//
// This is actually CLEANER than React because the compiler proves both
// branches produced a value — no runtime "token might be undefined" bugs.

<div class="auth-banner">${
    lin token = if (isAdmin()) {
        lift fetchAdminToken()
    } else {
        lift fetchUserToken()
    }

    // token declared. Consumed here, exactly once.
    lift <p class="token-display">Authenticated: ${token}/
}</>

// ======================================================================
// CASE B: lin in a loop with lift — where React instincts hit the wall
// ======================================================================
// React instinct: map() over items, pass token down to each row.
//   items.map(item => <Row key={item.id} token={token} item={item} />)
// The token is READ many times. React doesn't care — it's just a closure capture.
//
// lin cares. A lot.
//
// §34.4.4: lin SHALL NOT be consumed inside loop bodies. The loop is a
// potential multi-execution site. If you write `for (item of items) { useToken(lin) }`
// the compiler fires E-LIN-002 unconditionally — it doesn't check whether the
// loop runs 0 or 1000 times. The rejection is static and categorical.
//
// This is the sharpest React/scrml friction point for lin:
// In React, closing over a value in a map callback is the DEFAULT pattern.
// In scrml, that pattern is an error if the closed-over value is lin.
//
// Workaround: consume lin into a regular let BEFORE the loop.
// The let is unrestricted — closures, loops, whatever. Only lin has the constraint.

${
    function fetchBatchKey() -> string { return "batch-2026-04-10" }
}

<ul class="batch-list">${
    lin batchKey = fetchBatchKey()
    let batchLabel = batchKey        // lin consumed here (single use). batchLabel is free.
    let items = ?{`SELECT id, name FROM content ORDER BY id`}.all()

    for (let item of items) {
        lift <li class="batch-item" data-batch=batchLabel>
            <span>${item.id}/
            <span>${item.name}/
        </li>
    }
}</>

// ======================================================================
// CASE C: lin lifted across a component boundary — "context without Context"
// ======================================================================
// React mental model: you have a token. A deeply nested component needs it.
// Your options: useContext (implicit, global), prop drilling (explicit, verbose).
//
// scrml lin+lift is a third option: the value is produced at the parent logic
// context, consumed EXACTLY ONCE at the lift site (which is the outermost
// consumer), and the child just receives a plain value. No context object.
// No provider. No consumer. The compiler tracks it — you don't have to.
//
// §35.3 rule 4: "lift x where x is lin. The lift statement consumes x
// and initializes ~ to the lifted value."
// The component boundary is transparent to this — the lift site is in the parent.

${
    function loadSessionToken() -> string { return "sess-abc-xyz-789" }
}

<div class="app-shell">${
    lin sessionToken = loadSessionToken()

    // sessionToken consumed here at the lift site.
    // The child markup receives it as a data attribute — plain value, no lin tracking.
    // Compiler guarantee: sessionToken was not used before here, will not be used after.
    lift <div class="secure-panel" data-session=sessionToken>
        <h3>Secure Content/
        <p>Session established./
    </div>
}</>

</program>
